Got it. Setting up custom fonts and adding the typography plugin are great ways to enhance your project's design. Hereâ€™s how to correctly configure your `tailwind.config.js`.

### Step 1: Install the Typography Plugin

If you haven't already, you'll need to install the official Tailwind typography plugin.

```bash
npm install -D @tailwindcss/typography
```

### Step 2: Configure `tailwind.config.js`

Here is the complete configuration file. It adds the typography plugin and extends the default theme to include the 'Poppins' font family.

```javascript
/** @type {import('tailwindcss').Config} */
export default {
  content: [
    "./index.html",
    "./src/**/*.{js,ts,jsx,tsx}",
  ],
  theme: {
    extend: {
      fontFamily: {
        // You can name it whatever you want, but 'sans' is a good default
        // if you want Poppins to be the main font.
        // Or use a custom name like 'poppins' and apply it with `font-poppins`.
        poppins: ['Poppins', 'sans-serif'],
      },
    },
  },
  plugins: [
    require('@tailwindcss/typography'),
  ],
}
```

### Step 3: Import the Poppins Font

For the font to work, you need to import it into your project. The easiest way is to add it to your main CSS file (e.g., `src/index.css`).

```css
/* src/index.css */
@import url('https://fonts.googleapis.com/css2?family=Poppins:wght@400;700&display=swap');

@tailwind base;
@tailwind components;
@tailwind utilities;

/* You can also set it as the default font for the whole app here */
body {
  font-family: 'Poppins', sans-serif;
}
```

Now you can use the `font-poppins` utility class in your components, and the `prose` classes from the typography plugin will work automatically for styling your Markdown content.

